2 SENATE BILL 942
1 Article – Health – General
2 10–6A–02.
3 (b) This subtitle may not be construed to abridge or modify any civil right of the
4 respondent, including:
5 (1) Any civil service ranking or appointment;
6 (2) The right to apply for voluntary admission to a facility under § 10–609
7 of this title; and
8 (3) [Any] EXCEPT AS PROVIDED IN §§ 5–133 AND 5–205 OF THE
9 PUBLIC SAFETY ARTICLE AND THE PROVISIONS OF THIS SUBTITLE RELATING TO A
10 COURT’S ORDER PROHIBITING POSSESSION OF A FIREARM, ANY right relating to a
11 license, permit, certification, privilege, or benefit under any law.
12 10–6A–08.
13 (a) If, after hearing all relevant evidence, the court does not find by clear and
14 convincing evidence that the respondent meets the criteria for assisted outpatient
15 treatment, the court shall deny the petition.
16 (b) (1) If, after hearing all relevant evidence, the court finds by clear and
17 convincing evidence that the respondent meets the criteria for assisted outpatient
18 treatment, the court shall order the respondent to comply with assisted outpatient
19 treatment for a period not to exceed 1 year.
20 (2) The order of the court shall incorporate a treatment plan that:
21 (i) Is limited in scope to the elements included in the treatment plan
22 presented to the court under § 10–6A–06 of this subtitle; and
23 (ii) Includes only those elements that the court finds by clear and
24 convincing evidence to be essential to the maintenance of the respondent’s health or safety.
25 10–6A–08.1.
26 (A) IN THIS SECTION, “FIREARM” HAS THE MEANING STATED IN § 5–101 OF
27 THE PUBLIC SAFETY ARTICLE.
28 (B) (1) IF A COURT ORDERS A RESPONDENT TO COMPLY WITH ASSISTED
29 OUTPATIENT TREATMENT UNDER § 10–6A–08 OF THIS SUBTITLE, THE COURT SHALL
30 MAKE A DETERMINATION AS TO WHETHER THE RESPONDENT IS LIKELY TO
31 ENDANGER OR CAUSE PHYSICAL INJURY TO THE RESPONDENT OR ANOTHER IF THE
32 RESPONDENT HAS ACCESS TO A FIREARM.

SENATE BILL 942 3
1 (2) IF THE COURT DETERMINES THAT THE RESPONDENT IS LIKELY TO
2 ENDANGER OR CAUSE PHYSICAL INJURY TO THE RESPONDENT OR ANOTHER IF THE
3 RESPONDENT HAS ACCESS TO A FIREARM, THE COURT SHALL ORDER THE
4 RESPONDENT:
5 (I) TO SURRENDER TO LAW ENFORCEMENT AUTHORITIES ANY
6 FIREARM IN THE RESPONDENT’S POSSESSION; AND
7 (II) NOT TO PURCHASE OR POSSESS ANY FIREARM FOR THE
8 DURATION OF THE ORDER REQUIRING THE RESPONDENT TO COMPLY WITH
9 ASSISTED OUTPATIENT TREATMENT.
10 (C) (1) IN ACCORDANCE WITH THE PROVISIONS OF § 1–203 OF THE
11 CRIMINAL PROCEDURE ARTICLE, ON APPLICATION BY A STATE’S ATTORNEY OR A
12 LAW ENFORCEMENT OFFICER WITH PROBABLE CAUSE TO BELIEVE THAT A
13 RESPONDENT WHO IS SUBJECT TO AN ORDER UNDER THIS SECTION POSSESSES A
14 FIREARM AND FAILED TO SURRENDER THE FIREARM, A COURT MAY ISSUE A SEARCH
15 WARRANT FOR THE REMOVAL OF THE FIREARM AT ANY LOCATION IDENTIFIED IN
16 THE APPLICATION FOR THE WARRANT.
17 (2) (I) A COURT MAY ENFORCE AN ORDER UNDER THIS SECTION
18 THROUGH ITS CONTEMPT POWERS.
19 (II) THE COURT MAY IMPOSE ANY REASONABLE SANCTION FOR
20 A VIOLATION OF ITS ORDER UNDER THIS SECTION.
21 (D) AN ORDER UNDER SUBSECTION (B) OF THIS SECTION SHALL EXPIRE
22 WHEN THE RESPONDENT IS NO LONGER SUBJECT TO AN ORDER TO COMPLY WITH
23 ASSISTED OUTPATIENT TREATMENT UNDER § 10–6A–08 OF THIS SUBTITLE.
24 (E) IF A RESPONDENT SURRENDERS A FIREARM UNDER SUBSECTION (B) OF
25 THIS SECTION, A LAW ENFORCEMENT OFFICER SHALL:
26 (1) PROVIDE TO THE RESPONDENT INFORMATION ON THE PROCESS
27 FOR RETAKING POSSESSION OF THE FIREARM; AND
28 (2) TRANSPORT AND STORE THE FIREARM IN A PROTECTIVE CASE, IF
29 ONE IS AVAILABLE, AND IN A MANNER INTENDED TO PREVENT DAMAGE TO THE
30 FIREARM DURING THE TIME THE ORDER UNDER THIS SECTION IS IN EFFECT.
31 (F) THE RESPONDENT MAY RETAKE POSSESSION OF A SURRENDERED
32 FIREARM AT THE EXPIRATION OF THE COURT’S ORDER UNDER THIS SECTION,

4 SENATE BILL 942
1 UNLESS THE RESPONDENT IS NOT OTHERWISE LEGALLY ENTITLED TO OWN OR
2 POSSESS THE FIREARM.
3 (G) NOTWITHSTANDING ANY OTHER LAW, A RESPONDENT MAY TRANSPORT
4 A FIREARM IF THE RESPONDENT IS CARRYING AN ORDER ISSUED UNDER THIS
5 SECTION AND:
6 (1) THE FIREARM IS UNLOADED;
7 (2) THE RESPONDENT HAS NOTIFIED THE LAW ENFORCEMENT UNIT,
8 BARRACKS, OR STATION THAT THE FIREARM IS BEING TRANSPORTED IN
9 ACCORDANCE WITH THE COURT’S ORDER; AND
10 (3) THE RESPONDENT TRANSPORTS THE FIREARM DIRECTLY TO THE
11 LAW ENFORCEMENT UNIT, BARRACKS, OR STATION.
12 (H) (1) A LAW ENFORCEMENT OFFICER WHO TAKES POSSESSION OF A
13 FIREARM IN ACCORDANCE WITH AN ORDER UNDER THIS SECTION SHALL, AT THE
14 TIME THE FIREARM OR AMMUNITION IS SURRENDERED OR SEIZED:
15 (I) ISSUE A RECEIPT IDENTIFYING, BY MAKE, MODEL, AND
16 SERIAL NUMBER, ALL FIREARMS THAT HAVE BEEN SURRENDERED OR SEIZED;
17 (II) PROVIDE A COPY OF THE RECEIPT TO THE RESPONDENT;
18 (III) RETAIN A COPY OF THE RECEIPT; AND
19 (IV) PROVIDE INFORMATION TO THE RESPONDENT ON THE
20 PROCESS FOR RETAKING POSSESSION OF THE FIREARMS ON THE EXPIRATION OF
21 THE ORDER.
22 (2) A LAW ENFORCEMENT AGENCY SHALL TRANSPORT AND STORE
23 ANY FIREARM SURRENDERED OR SEIZED IN ACCORDANCE WITH AN ORDER UNDER
24 THIS SECTION:
25 (I) IN A PROTECTIVE CASE, IF ONE IS AVAILABLE; AND
26 (II) IN A MANNER INTENDED TO PREVENT DAMAGE TO THE
27 FIREARM DURING THE TIME THE ORDER IS IN EFFECT.
28 (3) A LAW ENFORCEMENT AGENCY MAY NOT PLACE ANY MARK ON A
29 SEIZED OR SURRENDERED FIREARM FOR IDENTIFICATION OR OTHER PURPOSES.

SENATE BILL 942 5
1 (4) (I) ON EXPIRATION OR TERMINATION OF AN ORDER UNDER
2 THIS SECTION, A LAW ENFORCEMENT AGENCY THAT HOLDS A FIREARM
3 SURRENDERED OR SEIZED IN ACCORDANCE WITH THE ORDER SHALL NOTIFY THE
4 RESPONDENT THAT THE RESPONDENT MAY REQUEST THE RETURN OF THE
5 FIREARM.
6 (II) A LAW ENFORCEMENT AGENCY SHALL RETURN A FIREARM
7 TO A RESPONDENT ONLY AFTER THE LAW ENFORCEMENT AGENCY VERIFIES THAT
8 THE RESPONDENT IS NOT OTHERWISE PROHIBITED FROM POSSESSING THE
9 FIREARM.
10 (III) SUBJECT TO SUBPARAGRAPH (II) OF THIS PARAGRAPH, ON
11 REQUEST OF THE RESPONDENT, A LAW ENFORCEMENT AGENCY SHALL RETURN ALL
12 FIREARMS BELONGING TO THE RESPONDENT NOT LATER THAN 48 HOURS AFTER
13 THE EXPIRATION OF AN ORDER UNDER THIS SECTION.
14 (5) (I) A RESPONDENT WHO DOES NOT WISH TO RECOVER A
15 FIREARM OR AMMUNITION SEIZED OR SURRENDERED IN ACCORDANCE WITH AN
16 ORDER UNDER THIS SECTION OR WHO IS PROHIBITED FROM POSSESSING FIREARMS
17 UNDER TITLE 5 OF THE PUBLIC SAFETY ARTICLE MAY:
18 1. SELL OR TRANSFER TITLE TO THE FIREARM TO:
19 A. A LICENSED FIREARMS DEALER; OR
20 B. ANOTHER INDIVIDUAL WHO IS NOT PROHIBITED
21 FROM POSSESSING THE FIREARM UNDER FEDERAL OR STATE LAW AND WHO DOES
22 NOT LIVE IN THE SAME RESIDENCE AS THE RESPONDENT; OR
23 2. REQUEST THE DESTRUCTION OF THE FIREARM.
24 (II) A LAW ENFORCEMENT AGENCY SHALL TRANSFER
25 POSSESSION OF A FIREARM OR AMMUNITION TO A LICENSED FIREARMS DEALER OR
26 AN INDIVIDUAL DESCRIBED IN SUBPARAGRAPH (I)1B OF THIS PARAGRAPH ONLY
27 AFTER:
28 1. THE LICENSED FIREARMS DEALER OR INDIVIDUAL
29 PROVIDES WRITTEN PROOF THAT THE RESPONDENT HAS AGREED TO TRANSFER THE
30 FIREARM TO THE DEALER OR INDIVIDUAL; AND
31 2. THE LAW ENFORCEMENT AGENCY VERIFIES THE
32 AGREEMENT WITH THE RESPONDENT.

6 SENATE BILL 942
1 (III) ON REQUEST OF THE RESPONDENT, A LAW ENFORCEMENT
2 AGENCY MAY DESTROY FIREARMS SEIZED OR SURRENDERED IN ACCORDANCE WITH
3 AN ORDER UNDER THIS SECTION.
4 (6) IF AN INDIVIDUAL OTHER THAN THE RESPONDENT CLAIMS
5 OWNERSHIP OF A FIREARM SEIZED OR SURRENDERED IN ACCORDANCE WITH AN
6 ORDER UNDER THIS SECTION, THE LAW ENFORCEMENT AGENCY SHALL RETURN THE
7 FIREARM TO THE INDIVIDUAL IF:
8 (I) THE INDIVIDUAL PROVIDES PROOF OF OWNERSHIP OF THE
9 FIREARM; AND
10 (II) THE LAW ENFORCEMENT AGENCY DETERMINES THAT THE
11 INDIVIDUAL IS NOT PROHIBITED FROM POSSESSING THE FIREARM OR AMMUNITION.
12 (7) IF A FIREARM IS NOT RECLAIMED WITHIN 6 MONTHS AFTER THE
13 PROVISION OF NOTICE TO A RESPONDENT UNDER PARAGRAPH (4) OF THIS
14 SUBSECTION:
15 (I) NO PARTY SHALL HAVE THE RIGHT TO ASSERT OWNERSHIP
16 OF THE FIREARM; AND
17 (II) THE LAW ENFORCEMENT AGENCY HOLDING THE FIREARM
18 MAY DESTROY THE FIREARM.
19 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect
20 October 1, 2026. It shall remain effective until the taking effect of the termination provision
21 specified in Section 3 of Chapter 704 of the Acts of the General Assembly of 2024. If that
22 termination provision takes effect, this Act shall be abrogated and of no further force and
23 effect. This Act may not be interpreted to have any effect on that termination provision.

